"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a one hour history of rapid onset of severe chest pain, not changing with the inspiration and not improving after rest. He also complains of pain going through to the back, worsening shortness of breath and fatigue. He is in severe pain but is able to answer all questions. He has a 30 year history of hypertension. He stopped smoking 20 years ago, drinks a glass of wine a day and uses cocaine at weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis temperature is 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, pulse 98/min, respiratory rate 17/min and blood pressure 160/90 mmHg in the right arm and 186/110 mmHg  in the left arm.  A diastolic murmur is heard at the left sternal border. A chest X-ray shows a widened mediastinum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transoesophageal echocardiography","Transthoracic echocardiography","CT angiography","ECG","Cardiac MRI"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has the clinical picture suggestive of an aortic dissection which includes sudden onset severe chest pain radiating to the back. Risk factors include hypertension(the most significant risk factor), Marfan\u0027s syndrome, cocaine use. On examination a\u00b1 \u0026gt;20 mm Hg variation in systolic blood pressure between both the arms is observed which is typical in patients with aortic dissection. The chest X-ray shows widened mediastinum. This patient also has aortic regurgitation (presence of diastolic murmur at left sternal border) which occurs as a complication of aortic dissection. This patient appears to be haemodynamically stable and \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography\u003C/strong\u003E would be the investigation of choice to provide a clear definition of the dissection. This investigation would show an intimal flap separating the true and false lumens in the aorta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransoesophageal echocardiography\u003C/strong\u003E is done as an investigation of choice in aortic dissection patients with haemodynamic instability or renal insufficiency and in whom time is of the essence, to minimise any delay in surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransthoracic echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E may not visualise parts of the aorta well, therefore is not performed in patients with aortic dissection. It is a confirmatory test in patients with blunt cardiac injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EECG\u003C/strong\u003E findings can include ST-segment changes, T-wave inversions, and Q waves and these changes are related to the aortic dissection extending into the coronary artery origins. Thus ECG findings alone cannot definitively diagnose aortic dissection and further imaging studies are often necessary. Therefore it is not a confirmatory test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst \u003Cstrong\u003Ecardiac MRI\u003C/strong\u003E can provide detailed images of the heart and aorta to help identify the location and extent of the dissection, it is never used in acute aortic dissections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with aortic dissection who are haemodynamically stable, CT angiography is performed as a confirmatory test and transoesophageal echocardiography is performed in haemodynamically unstable patients."],"references":["Escabi-Mendoza J, Diaz-Rodriguez PE, Gonzalez-Bravo DH, Partida-Rodriguez E. An Unexpected Cause of Chest Pain While Self-Pleasuring: A Ripping Doom Excitement. Cureus. 2023 May 2;15(5):e38436. doi: 10.7759/cureus.38436. PMID: 37273370; PMCID: PMC10234142."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89546"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13013"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"